"in a conflict civilians are often caught between two evils. If they stay in their homes, they are exposed to the dangers of war (bombing, landmines, attacks, famine) and are apt to find themselves without means or medical care. If they flee, they are still at the mercy of the combatants, as potential hostages risking arrest, summary execution, or ''disappearance.'' Such population movements, spontaneous at first, are apt to become forced, where the armed forces seek to isolate insurgents. People displaced within their own country are protected by Article 3 and Protocol II. \n# Population Displacements\nThe protection of refugee populations poses specific problems."